{
  "hook": "Your PCB design choices are silently eating your budget.",
  "headline": "DFM Mistakes That Add Cost to Your PCB",
  "body": [
    "Most PCB cost overruns come from avoidable design choices.",
    "Blind and buried vias can add up to 40% to fabrication costs.",
    "Dual sided assembly increases costs by 20 to 30 percent.",
    "Poor spacing causes solder bridges and rework loops.",
    "Missing or corrupted Gerber files halt production entirely."
  ],
  "insight": "A DFM optimized design with standard materials and minimal layers can cut production costs by up to 40% compared to a non compliant design.",
  "source": "JLCPCB, ALLPCB, Sierra Circuits",
  "source_url": "https://jlcpcb.com/blog/dfm-analysis-in-pcb-design",
  "pillar": "manufacturing",
  "account": "cu-circuits",
  "hashtags": ["#PCB", "#DFM", "#DesignForManufacturing", "#CuCircuits", "#PCBDesign", "#MakeInIndia", "#HardwareEngineering"],
  "caption": "Your design choices are quietly inflating your PCB costs.\n\nHere's a visual breakdown of where the money actually goes when DFM rules are ignored.\n\nBlind and buried vias? That's +40% on fab costs alone.\nDual sided assembly? Another 20 to 30% added.\nPremium surface finishes like ENIG? 10 to 20% more.\n\nAnd the hidden costs of rework, supplier back and forth, and test failures? Those are the ones that really hurt.\n\nThe fix is simple: run a DFM check before you send your Gerbers. Optimize layer count. Use standard materials. Avoid unnecessary complexity.\n\nA well optimized design can cut production costs by up to 40%.\n\nAt Cu Circuits, we review every design for manufacturability before it hits the floor.\n\nSave this for your next tape out.\n\n#PCB #DFM #DesignForManufacturing #CuCircuits #PCBDesign #MakeInIndia #HardwareEngineering",
